quran[4]{c,v,t,f}:
  2,249,"So when Talut<sup>a </sup>set out with the troops, he said, “Allah will indeed be testing you with a river. So whoever drinks from it does not belong with me, but whoever does not taste it does belong with me—except for whoever scoops up a scoopful{1}with his hand.” Yet they drank from it, except for a few of them. Then when he had crossed it together with those who had attained faith with him, they said, “We have no strength to face Galut{2}and his troops today.” Those expecting to meet Allah said, “How many a small battalion has overcome a large battalion by Allah’s leave, for Allah is with the patient ones.”",footnotes:1:[Saul.]
  2,250,"And when they confronted Galut<sup>d </sup>and his troops, they said, “Our Lord, pour down patience upon us and strengthen our foothold and support us against the denying people.”",footnotes:1:[Goliath.]
  2,251,"So they defeated them by Allah’s leave when David killed Galut<sup>d </sup>, and Allah brought him authority and wisdom and taught him as He willed. And were it not for Allah repelling{1}some people by means of others, the earth would indeed become corrupted, but Allah is Gracious to all realms.",footnotes:1:[Goliath.],footnotes:2:[Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “And were it not for Allah strongly repelling some people…”]
  2,252,"Those are Allah’s signs{1}which We read to you in truth, for you are most surely one of the emissaries.",footnotes:1:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.]
